         <abstract>
            <p>A Chebyshev quadrature is of the form ∫&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;-1&lt;/sub&gt; w(x)f(x)dx ≃ c ∑&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;k=1&lt;/sub&gt; f(x&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;). It is usually desirable that the nodes x&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; be in the interval of integration and that the quadrature be exact for as many monomials as possible (i.e., the first n + 1 monomials). For n = 1, ⋯, 7 and 9, such a choice of nodes is possible, but for n = 8 and &lt;latex&gt;$n &gt; 9$&lt;/latex&gt;, the nodes are complex. In this note, the idea used is that the l&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;-norm of the deviations of the first n + 1 monomials from their moments be a minimum. Numerical calculations are carried out for n = 8, 10 and 11 and one interesting feature of the numerical results is that a "multiple" node at the origin is required. The above idea is then generalized to a minimization of the l&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;-norm of the deviations of the first k monomials, k ≥ n + 1, including k = ∞, and corresponding numerical results are presented.</p>
          </abstract>
